June 2, 2026

****Market Performance****

****Trending on TIKR****

Alphabet (NASDAQ: GOOGL) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D29096&tid=
=3D11311662: Alphabet is making headlines after unveiling plans to raise $8=
0 billion in stock to fund its AI buildout. The package includes $30 billio=
n in underwritten offerings, a $40 billion at-the-market program starting i=
n Q3, and a $10 billion private placement bought directly by Berkshire Hath=
away, now led by new CEO Greg Abel. The cash backs capital spending that ma=
nagement has guided as high as $190 billion this year, roughly double 2025.

Hewlett Packard Enterprise (NYSE: HPE) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=
=3D273983758&tid=3D313064514: HPE, which sells the servers, storage, and ne=
tworking gear companies use to run their data centers and AI systems, climb=
ed over 9% Monday and then jumped roughly 30% after hours on a blowout quar=
ter. Revenue rose about 40% to $10.7 billion, and the company nearly double=
d both its AI orders and its AI backlog versus a year ago. Management sharp=
ly raised guidance, lifting its full-year adjusted earnings outlook to arou=
nd $3.40 a share from roughly $2.40 and pushing revenue growth toward the 3=
0% range. After years as the sleepy half of the old HP, HPE is suddenly rid=
ing the AI infrastructure wave hard.

Nvidia (NASDAQ: NVDA) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D32307&tid=3D26=
35154: Nvidia rose over 6% Monday as CEO Jensen Huang used his Computex key=
note in Taipei to push the company into brand-new territory. The headline w=
as the RTX Spark, Nvidia's first processor built for Windows PCs, an Arm-ba=
sed chip co-developed with Microsoft and MediaTek that lands in laptops fro=
m Dell, Lenovo, and HP this fall. Huang framed it as the first true reinven=
tion of the PC in 40 years. The move plants Nvidia squarely in a market it =
has never competed in, and investors clearly liked the idea of the AI chip =
leader opening up an entirely new multi-billion-dollar revenue line.

Intel (NASDAQ: INTC) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D21127&tid=3D262=
1295: Intel, the chipmaker whose processors have powered most of the world'=
s Windows PCs for four decades, fell nearly 5% as the other side of Nvidia'=
s announcement played out. Nvidia's new chip directly targets the processor=
 market that Intel and AMD have split between them since the 1980s, and Wal=
l Street read it as a real threat to one of Intel's core businesses. Intel =
tried to counter with its own new data-center chip, but the launch got drow=
ned out, and Northland Capital downgraded the stock. The selloff says inves=
tors think Intel's turf just got a lot smaller.

Taylor Morrison Home (NYSE: TMHC) https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D22=
4946128&tid=3D234239320: Taylor Morrison, one of the largest homebuilders i=
n the US, jumped about 22% after Berkshire Hathaway agreed to buy it for $7=
2.50 a share in cash, a deal worth roughly $6.8 billion. The price is a 24%=
 premium to Friday's close, and the shares snapped almost right up to the o=
ffer. It is the first big acquisition under new Berkshire CEO Greg Abel, an=
d pairing Taylor Morrison with Berkshire's existing Clayton Homes would mak=
e the conglomerate one of the four largest US homebuilders. The move reads =
as a bet that American housing demand recovers, even with mortgage rates ne=
ar multi-year highs.

