**Lumentum (NASDAQ: LITE): Why Analysts Are Forecasting Revenue to Roughly =
5x by FY 2028**

Lumentum makes the lasers and optical parts that move data around as pulses=
 of light, the technology that shuttles information between the chips insid=
e AI data centers and across the buildings that house them. It was spun out=
 of telecom-equipment maker JDS Uniphase back in 2015, and for years it was=
 a fairly sleepy supplier tied to phone networks and the sensors behind App=
le's Face ID. The AI boom changed everything. Analysts now expect revenue t=
o climb from about $1.6 billion in fiscal 2025 to over $8 billion by fiscal=
 2028, roughly a 5x jump, with growth topping 80% in each of the next two y=
ears.

https://app.tikr.com/stock/financials?cid=3DPLACEHOLDER_CID&tid=3DPLACEHOLD=
ER_TID&tab=3Dis=20

A few things are driving that. The biggest is cloud transceivers, the optic=
al modules that connect AI chips to each other at very high speeds. Lumentu=
m's most recent quarter saw revenue jump about 90% to a record $808 million=
, led by these parts as customers upgrade their networks to faster standard=
s. Two newer products add fuel: optical circuit switches, which let data ce=
nters rewire their connections on the fly to save power, and co-packaged op=
tics, which build the light-handling pieces directly onto chips. Switch bac=
klog alone has already passed $400 million.

The catch, and the reason the forecast looks credible rather than hopeful, =
is that demand is outrunning supply. Lumentum says it is short-shipping cus=
tomers by around 30% because it cannot make these laser chips fast enough, =
and Nvidia signed a multi-year partnership with the company earlier this ye=
ar.

