****The Week Ahead****

A loaded week of prints across AI hardware, cybersecurity, healthcare, and =
the consumer, capped by Friday's May jobs report. Here are the five events =
worth watching:

**Tuesday, June 2**

*=20

**Palo Alto Networks (NASDAQ: PANW), After Close:** The cybersecurity giant=
 is expected to post revenue around $2.9 billion, up about 28%, with earnin=
gs near $0.80. Much of that growth comes from its recent CyberArk acquisiti=
on, so investors will zero in on organic momentum and next-generation secur=
ity ARR guided near $8 billion. With the stock up over 50% this year, expec=
tations are high and any soft guidance could sting.

**Wednesday, June 3**

*=20

**Medtronic (NYSE: MDT), Before Open:** One of the world's biggest medical-=
device makers (pacemakers, insulin pumps, surgical tools) closes its fiscal=
 year with full-year adjusted earnings guided to roughly $5.50 a share. Wat=
ch for the drag from carving out its diabetes unit, MiniMed, and any read o=
n whether device demand and hospital procedure volumes are holding up. Medt=
ronic is a useful health-of-healthcare bellwether.

*=20

**Broadcom (NASDAQ: AVGO), After Close:** The biggest print of the week. Br=
oadcom designs custom AI chips for the largest cloud companies and is expec=
ted to report revenue around $22 billion, up roughly 47%, with AI chip sale=
s near $10.7 billion. Investors want an updated order backlog after recent =
deals with Google and Meta. As the main Nvidia alternative, Broadcom's numb=
ers set the tone for the whole AI hardware trade.

**Thursday, June 4**

*=20

**Ciena (NYSE: CIEN), Before Open:** Ciena builds the optical gear that car=
ries traffic between data centers, and it has become a key beneficiary of A=
I-driven network demand. Management guided revenue near $1.5 billion, with =
the full-year outlook implying growth around 28%. After a monster prior qua=
rter, watch gross margins and any comments on how aggressively cloud giants=
 are buying. A strong print would echo the Lumentum story above.

*=20

**Lululemon (NASDAQ: LULU), After Close:** The athletic-apparel brand is ex=
pected to grow revenue only about 3% to roughly $2.4 billion, with earnings=
 down around 36% to near $1.67. Soft North American demand and tariff press=
ure are the worries. After a rough stretch for the stock, this report is a =
real test of whether the brand still has pricing power, and a useful gauge =
of the higher-end US consumer.

